Auction frontend folder has the React frontend application, other folder has the API built by .net Core

To login either use Joe => 123, or Mike => 456 username password combinations

You could run the following SQL Query to create your tables and update the connection string to start the application:

create table dbo.AutoBid(
Id int Identity(1,1),
BidderId int FOREIGN KEY REFERENCES dbo.Bidder(Id),
ItemId int FOREIGN KEY REFERENCES dbo.Item(Id),
Budget int,
PRIMARY KEY (Id)
)

create table dbo.Bid(
Id int Identity(1,1),
BidderId int FOREIGN KEY REFERENCES dbo.Bidder(Id),
ItemId int FOREIGN KEY REFERENCES dbo.Item(Id),
Offer int,
TimeOfBidding datetime,
ItemExpiry datetime,
AutoBid BIT,
PRIMARY KEY (Id),
)

create table dbo.Bidder(
Id int Identity(1,1),
Name varchar(500),
PRIMARY KEY (Id)
)

create table dbo.Item(
Id int Identity(1,1),
Name varchar(500),
Description varchar(2000),
Expiry datetime,
Image varchar(max) Default '',
LastPrice int Default 0
PRIMARY KEY (Id)
)

/*Afterwards if you want to insert few bidders and items you can run the following:*/

insert into dbo.Bidder values('Bidder Joe')
insert into dbo.Bidder values('Bidder Mike')

/*You could put any image, just convert one to base64 first*/
DECLARE @Img AS VARCHAR(max)
SET @Img = ''

insert into dbo.Item values('Golden Clock','Fully gold', '08/27/2021 12:00:00 AM', @Img,11)
insert into dbo.Item values('Clock of the Century', 'Works even in space', '08/29/2021 6:10:00 PM', @Img,13)
